ey Scott's Blade Runner, based on Philip K. Dick's novel Do Androids Dream of Electric Sheep?, has remained a cult classic through its depiction of a futuristic Los Angeles; its complex, enigmatic plot; and its underlying questions about the nature of human identity. The Blade Runner Experience: The Legacy of a Science Fiction Classic examines the film in a broad context, examining its relationship to the original novel, the PC game, the series of sequels, and the many films influenced by its style and themes. It investigates Blade Runner online fandom and asks how the film's future city compares to the present-day Los Angeles, and it revisits the film to pose surprising new questions about its characters and their world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aScience fiction filmsxHistory and criticism. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh1 aAlessio, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtkins, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarlow, Aaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooker, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooker, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooker, Will, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGray, Christy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGray, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHills, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJermyn, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerman, Judith B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLacey, Nick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/v